{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe enriched sidecars (stories 4e19/7c84/e7e0) and the existing attestations are reachable today\nonly via scattered internal helpers; there is no single call that returns a ticket's FULL retained\nreview history or resolves its associated code reviews. The follow-on audit UI epic and any script\nneed one documented read surface.\n\n## What\n\nA read layer that, for a ticket id, returns: (a) the full retained history (not just latest) of\nplan-review sidecars; (b) the completion attestation plus any completion sidecar record; (c) the\nassociated code reviews, resolved via the ticket's inbound `relates_to` links from `code_review`\ntickets, each with its full sidecar history. Exposed as a library function, a CLI command, and a\nread-only MCP tool.\n\n## Data contract (the returned typed dict)\n\n`audit_trail(ticket_id)` returns a `TypedDict` with EXACT key names and nullability:\n\n```python\nclass CompletionRecord(TypedDict):\n    attestation: dict | None   # the ticket's completion-verifier attestation (from show/keyring); None if unsigned\n    sidecar: dict | None       # the latest completion sidecar record â€” a PASS (completion_verifier_pass_v1)\n                               # or FAIL (completion_verifier_fail_v1) record; None if no sidecar event\n\nclass AuditTrail(TypedDict):\n    ticket: dict                    # the ticket's current details (from rebar.show)\n    plan_reviews: list[dict]        # full retained plan-review sidecar history, newest-first; [] if none\n    completion: CompletionRecord | None  # None ONLY when BOTH attestation AND sidecar are absent\n    code_reviews: list[dict]        # each: {ticket_id, sidecars: list[dict]} â€” a linked code_review\n                                    # ticket + its own newest-first sidecar history; [] if none\n```\n\n- `plan_reviews` is ALWAYS a list (empty `[]` when the ticket has no plan-review sidecars), newest first.\n- `completion` is a `CompletionRecord` dict when EITHER a completion-verifier attestation OR a\n  completion sidecar record exists; it is `None` ONLY when BOTH are absent. The two sub-fields come\n  from two DISJOINT sources (the attestation lives on the ticket; the sidecar is a `COMPLETION_VERDICT`\n  event), so each is independently nullable inside the record.\n- `code_reviews` is ALWAYS a list (empty `[]` when no `code_review` ticket links to this ticket via\n  `relates_to`); each entry carries its OWN sidecar history list.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py` and `src/rebar/llm/code_review/sidecar.py` â€” add\n  `all_review_results(ticket)` history enumerators (walk the ticket's `REVIEW_RESULT` events\n  newestâ†’oldest, schema-tolerant, returning the list of payload dicts; `[]` on missing/error),\n  complementing the existing `latest_*` readers.\n- `src/rebar/llm/completion_sidecar.py` â€” the completion sidecar reader for the `completion.sidecar`\n  field: reuse `latest_pass_record` (PASS) and `latest_fail_verdict` (FAIL) â€” the aggregator returns\n  whichever is newest/present (no new reader needed unless a \"latest of either kind\" helper is\n  cleaner; if added, keep it schema-tolerant over both `completion_verifier_pass_v1` and `_fail_v1`).\n- New `src/rebar/audit/read.py` â€” an `audit_trail(ticket_id, *, repo_root=None)` aggregator composing\n  the plan / completion / code-review histories, resolving code reviews via the ticket's inbound\n  `relates_to` links from `code_review` tickets (reusing `rebar.show` / `rebar.list_tickets`),\n  returning the `AuditTrail` typed dict above. Also add `__init__.py` for the new `rebar.audit`\n  package.\n- CLI registration (owns-its-own-`--help` intercept pattern used by `_workflow`/`_llm`/`_criteria`):\n  - add an `audit` intercept in `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py::main`, dispatching to an\n    `audit_cli(rest)` handler in a new `src/rebar/_cli/_audit_commands.py` (parses\n    `show <ticket> [--output json]` and prints the `AuditTrail`).\n  - **create `src/rebar/_cli/help/audit.txt`** (the usage text for `rebar audit show`). This is what\n    makes `audit` a recognized subcommand: `known_subcommands()` is NOT a hardcoded set â€” it is\n    DERIVED from the `.txt` files under `src/rebar/_cli/help/` (every `<name>.txt` except\n    `overview.txt`). So adding the help file registers the subcommand; do NOT edit `known_subcommands`.\n- MCP read-tool registration: add a read-only `audit_trail(ticket_id)` tool inside\n  `src/rebar/_mcp_reads.py::register_read_tools` (decorated with `@mcp.tool(annotations=_ANN\n  [\"READ_ONLY\"])`, like the other read tools), so it is available even under `REBAR_MCP_READONLY=1`.\n\n## Approach rationale\n\nA single aggregator over the existing readers + the existing `relates_to` links reuses the linkage\nthe reviewbot already writes (`emit_code_review_artifact` links each code-review artifact\n`relates_to` its work ticket), so no new linking mechanism is introduced â€” the read layer only\ntraverses links that already exist. The MCP tool is read-only so it is available regardless of\n`REBAR_MCP_READONLY`.\n\n## Compatibility & rollback\n\nPure addition (new readers + new command + new read-only tool); no existing behavior changes.\nSchema-tolerant readers accept both v1 and v2 records. Reverting removes the new surface (delete\n`rebar.audit`, `_audit_commands.py`, `help/audit.txt`, the intercept, the MCP tool, the\n`all_review_results` readers) with no data impact.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `audit_trail(ticket_id)` returns a dict with EXACTLY the keys `ticket`, `plan_reviews`,\n      `completion`, `code_reviews`; `plan_reviews` and `code_reviews` are lists (newest-first,\n      `[]` when none), `completion` is `CompletionRecord | None` (`None` only when both attestation\n      and sidecar are absent). Oracle: an integration test seeding a ticket with multiple plan-review\n      sidecars, a completion record, and a `relates_to`-linked `code_review` ticket with its own\n      sidecar, then asserting the exact key set, the newest-first ordering of `plan_reviews`, that\n      `completion` is a dict, and that `code_reviews[0]` carries its own sidecar history; plus a\n      companion assertion that a bare ticket yields `plan_reviews == []`, `completion is None`,\n      `code_reviews == []`.\n- [ ] `rebar audit show <ticket> --output json` prints the same structure. Oracle: a CLI subprocess\n      test asserting on the emitted JSON's key set.\n- [ ] The MCP `audit_trail` tool returns the structure and is read-only (available even with\n      `REBAR_MCP_READONLY=1`). Oracle: a test invoking the tool handler under that env.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784078383568442001,"uuid":"409710d0-be28-4fc1-b544-b5cf7de2b63c"}